properties.name: Goulburn River
properties.description: The Goulburn River is large tailwater that flows from the Lake Eildon Pondage. The river flows clear and has a freestone bottom with a mixture of weed beds and occasional timber. It flows through flat farmland with intermittent riparian vegetation, often in the form of willows...

properties.name: Blue Rock Dam
properties.description: A large water storage located east of Melbourne next to the town of Willow Grove. The lake is fed by the Tanjil River which has some very good fishing both above and below the dam...

properties.name: Deepwater River
properties.description: Deepwater River is a small-to-medium sized perennial stream in the Northern Tablelands district of New South Wales. It runs through the small town of Deepwater, which has amenities for travelling anglers...

properties.name: Guy Fawkes River
properties.description: The Guy Fawkes River is a perennial stream in the New England and Northern Tablelands districts of New South Wales. The river is a small meandering stream that winds its way down from its headwaters near the Great Escarpment, through farmland and the township of Ebor, and over the Ebor Falls...

properties.name: Arthurs Lake
properties.description: One of the most well know and popular fisheries in Tasmania’s central plates, Arthurs lake is a large body of water managed for hydro electricity generation. It holds a large population of wild brown trout that are self sustaining, spawning in the many creeks and streams running into the lake...

properties.name: Bronte Lagoon
properties.description: There are great grassy shorelines around the lake that you can expect to find tailing trout along, so long as the water level is high. Early season wet fly fishing is very good, with plenty of structure to focus on including weed beds, rocky shorelines, points and fallen timber...

properties.name: Brumbys Creek
properties.description: Brumbys Creek is one of Tasmania’s most unique rivers. It is like a tailwater in that it is fed from Great Lake in the Central Highlands via the Poatina Power Station, however, it flows more like a meadow stream...

properties.name: Lake Huntsman
properties.description: Created in 2007, Lake Huntsman is a scenic dam nestled atop of the Meander Valley. The lake is surround by forest and is fed by a number of small streams and holds a large population of small wild brown trout...

properties.name: Huon River
properties.description: The Huon is a big river, being the fifth longest in the state. Initially the river flows through rugged terrain, lower down it becomes more accessible as it moves through farmland and towns before meeting the sea...

properties.name: Lake Burbury
properties.description: Lake Burbury is a large and beautiful waterway on the west coast. It contains a good head of rainbow and brown trout. This lake is typically considered as a venue best fished from a boat, purely because of its size...

properties.name: Lake Leake
properties.description: A scenic lake nestled in the hills of the east coast, Lake Leake is surrounded by lowland forest. Due to its lack of height above sea level, it fishes well early in the season before the water warms too much...

properties.name: Lake St Clair
properties.description: Arguably the most scenic lake in Tasmania and located within the Cradle Mountain-Lake St Clair National Park, Lake St Clair is a trekking destination as part of the Overland Track and a stunning wild brown and rainbow trout fishery...

properties.name: Little Pine Lagoon
properties.description: Little Pine Lagoon is one of Australia’s best-known wild brown trout fisheries and is dedicated fly-fishing-only water. It is fed from the Little Pine River and releases water down the Monpeelyata Canal to Lake Echo...

properties.name: Macquarie River
properties.description: he Macquarie River is a picturesque slow flowing meadow stream with banks lined by grass and tussocks and some sections of willows. Running through the midlands of Tasmania, this river provides plenty of access to anglers...

properties.name: Meander River
properties.description: The Meander River is a tailwater that runs out of Huntsman Dam, flowing through forest and then farmland on its journey to join the South Esk River. It flows cold and clear all season long and contains a good population of wild brown trout...

properties.name: Mersey River
properties.description: The Mersey River is a long watercourse and technically a tail water, however, it has many tributaries running into it as is flows north draining into the Bass Strait at Devonport. The Mersey is a medium sized freestone river...

properties.name: North Esk River
properties.description: The North Esk is a long river system that forms in the forested valleys of the Northallerton Valley. It winds through a combination of forest and open farm land that features quite a lot of willows along the bank, it then travels through the suburbs of Launceston on its way to form the Tamar River...

properties.name: Penstock Lagoon
properties.description: One of the most popular waters in the highlands, Penstock Lagoon is a fly-fishing-only lake known for its mayfly fishing. The lake is shallow and weedy and contains a mix of wild brown trout and stocked rainbow trout...

properties.name: Pine Tier Lagoon
properties.description: Pine Tier is a little gem of a lake situated in the hills off the back of the Central Plateau. It is an intimate lake that is long and narrow with two rivers running in; Pine River and the Nive River...

properties.name: South Esk River
properties.description: The South Esk is the longest and one of the most diverse rivers in Tasmania. You can find fishable water at the source, near Upper Esk, all the way to Trevallyn Dam before it flows into the Tamar River...

properties.name: St Patricks River
properties.description: The St Patricks River, known as the St Pats, is a stunning freestone stream lined by a combination of willows and native vegetation. This stream holds a large population of wild brown trout...

properties.name: Tooms Lake
properties.description: Tooms Lake is another lowland water supply along the east coast, located south-west of the town of Ross. Bordered by forest reserve, it is a very scenic waterway to fish. The lake is shallow and has limited natural recruitment...

properties.name: Tyenna River
properties.description: A beautiful medium-sized river running through Maydena, Tyenna and other quaint country towns, the Tyenna River provides good fly fishing from late spring through to the close of the season. The river is predominantly freestone with some sections of bedrock...

properties.name: Weld River
properties.description: A rugged, wild medium-sized, tannin-stained river, the Weld River runs through forest until it meets the Huon River. The wading is challenging with plenty of boulders and timber, however, there is some fantastic fly fishing to be had...

properties.name: Coliban River
properties.description: An intimate little river/creek that flows out of forest into open farmland before flowing into the Upper Coliban Reservoir. The bottom structure of the river is a combination of bedrock, gravel, strap weed and fallen timber...

properties.name: Eildon Pondage
properties.description: Located between Lake Eildon and the Goulburn River, ‘the Pondage’ is a medium sized man made lake that holds up water before it is released down the Goulburn River. The lake bottom is quite baron and the structure mostly comes in the form depressions and ledges...

properties.name: King Parrot Creek
properties.description: A small to medium sized tributary of the Goulburn River, it flows north off the back of the Kinglake National Park through Flowerdale and enters the Goulburn River just upstream of Trawool. The bottom structure of the river varies greatly, it is a mixture of freestone, gravel/sand, bedrock and timber...

properties.name: Lake Fyans
properties.description: Lake Fyans is a very scenic trout fishery located on the eastern side of the Grampians, it is a mostly shallow, medium sized lake with treed shorelines and sandy or rocky edges. The lake features a range of different structure including weed beds, thick rushes and reeds, sandy flats and sunken timber...

properties.name: Lake Purrumbete
properties.description: Lake Purrumbete is a crystal clear trout fishery set inside and volcanic crater. It is an extremely fertile lake filled with lush wed beds, an abundance of food and as a result, trout with extremely fast growth rates...

properties.name: Lake Wendouree
properties.description: Lake Wendouree is a unique trout fishery in that it is located in the middle of the rural city of Ballarat. It is a medium sized lake and is very shallow, most of the lake is around five feet deep. It contains of lush weed beds, reed banks, small islands, rocky shorelines...

properties.name: Lake William Hovell
properties.description: A medium sized dam located on the King River in the King Valley not far from Wangarrata. The lake is surrounded by forest and is well protected from the weather, the lake consists of sand/silt bottoms with some weed beds, timbered bays and rocky ledges...

properties.name: Loch River
properties.description: The Loch is a small and tight stream that flows into the La Trobe River in Noojee. It has a combination of freestone and gravel bottom and is lined by tree ferns and beautiful green riparian vegetation...

properties.name: Big River (Upper Mitta Mitta)
properties.description: Arguably Victoria’s best high country trout river, the Mitta Mitta is a pristine medium to large sized freestone river with a large population of brown and rainbow trout. This river originates in the Alpine National park and flows through the Omeo Valley on its way into Lake Dartmouth...

properties.name: Mitta Mitta River (Upper)
properties.description: Arguably Victoria’s best high country trout river, the Mitta Mitta is a pristine medium to large sized freestone river with a large population of brown and rainbow trout. This river originates in the Alpine National park and flows through the Omeo Valley on its way into Lake Dartmouth...

properties.name: Newlyn Reservoir
properties.description: A medium sized water storage located west of Melbourne near the towns of Daylesford and Creswick. The lake is surrounded by farmland with a combination of grassy, rocky and willowed shorelines...

properties.name: Ovens River
properties.description: The Ovens River is clear freestone high country stream that originates in the Victorian Alps. It flows through a combination of forest, plantations and farmland on its journey to join the Murray River above Lake Mulwala...

properties.name: Rocky Valley Storage
properties.description: Rocky Valley Storage reservoir is a beautiful alpine water storage located next to Falls Creek. As the name suggests the lake is very rocky and barren with limited grass and weed, despite this the lake has an extremely large population of small wild brown and rainbow trout...

properties.name: Rubicon River
properties.description: A popular freestone river flowing out of forest and then through farmland before in joins the Goulburn River. The upper section is fast flowing and features many large boulders and pocket water...

properties.name: Steavenson River
properties.description: A beautifully clear freestone stream that holds a large population of wild brown and rainbow trout. It is one of the most popular fly fishing rivers in Victoria due to its productivity, access and proximity to Melbourne...

properties.name: Toorongo River
properties.description: A beautiful, small scenic river that flows out of temperate rainforest into open farmland before meeting the La Trobe River. High in the system the river is crystal clear and the bottom freestone featuring larger boulders...

properties.name: Wombat Reservoir
properties.description: Wombat Reservoir is very scenic and intimate lake surround forest located near the town of Daylesford. It is domestic water supply with good water quality and a good population of brown trout...

properties.name: Yarra River (upper)
properties.description: A very underrated trout stream close to Melbourne, the Yarra River is a medium sized tailwater that flows from the Upper Yarra Reservoir and empties into Port Phillip Bay in Melbourne. Naturally the best trout fishing is up in the higher sections...

properties.name: Cairn Curran Reservoir
properties.description: Cairn Curran Reservoir is a large dam located on the Loddon River west of the town of Castlemaine. The lake features many grassy shorelines, rocky edges, weed beds and standing timber. This is a unique lake in the way it is managed as mixed fishery...
